    <section id="introduction" class="reveal">
      <p>In 1938, a DuPont chemist named Roy Plunkett accidentally created polytetrafluoroethylene — better known as Teflon — a slippery white substance so chemically inert it could resist nearly anything. Its first application was military: coating valves and seals handling corrosive uranium compounds during the Manhattan Project. This was, by any standard, a material designed for extreme industrial use.</p>

      <p>By the 1950s, DuPont had repackaged this military-grade chemical coating as a consumer kitchen product, promising homemakers liberation from scrubbing pans. The marketing was brilliant. The science behind what happened next was not.</p>

      <p>What DuPont knew — and what internal documents later revealed during litigation — was that the manufacturing process for non-stick coatings produced a class of chemicals with a property unique in industrial chemistry: <strong>they do not break down</strong>. Not in the environment. Not in water treatment. Not in the human body. The industry's own term for them is now common parlance: <em>forever chemicals</em>.</p>
    </section>

    <section id="forever-chemicals" class="reveal">
      <h2>Why "Forever Chemicals" Are a Legitimate Concern</h2>

      <p>PFOA (perfluorooctanoic acid), the key chemical used in manufacturing Teflon coatings, belongs to a broader family called PFAS — per- and polyfluoroalkyl substances. The carbon-fluorine bond at the core of these molecules is one of the strongest in organic chemistry. As Dr. Linda Birnbaum, former director of the National Institute of Environmental Health Sciences, has noted, this bond "barely exists in nature." It was engineered in a lab, and nature has no mechanism to undo it.</p>

      <p>Once ingested, PFAS accumulate in the body with a half-life measured in <strong>years</strong>, not days. The health consequences documented in peer-reviewed research are significant:</p>

      <ul>
        <li><strong>Cancer:</strong> Increased risk of kidney, testicular, and prostate cancers. A 2023 study found PFAS exposure increases thyroid cancer risk by <strong>56%</strong></li>
        <li><strong>Reproductive harm:</strong> Fertility issues, pregnancy complications, and developmental problems in children</li>
        <li><strong>Liver damage:</strong> Elevated cholesterol and compromised hepatic function</li>
        <li><strong>Immune suppression:</strong> Weakened vaccine response and reduced immune function</li>
        <li><strong>Endocrine disruption:</strong> Thyroid dysfunction and hormonal interference</li>
      </ul>

      <p>These are not fringe findings. The epidemiological data comes from large-scale studies of communities living near PFAS manufacturing facilities, where exposure levels are highest and health outcomes are most clearly linked to contamination.</p>
    </section>

    <aside class="pull-quote reveal">
      <p>"The carbon-fluorine bond barely exists in nature. It was engineered in a lab, and nature has no mechanism to undo it."</p>
    </aside>

    <section id="beyond-kitchen" class="reveal">
      <h2>Beyond Your Kitchen: The Scale of Contamination</h2>

      <p>The uncomfortable reality is that non-stick cookware is only one exposure route — and probably not even the primary one for most people. PFAS chemicals appear in waterproof clothing, food packaging, stain-resistant carpets and upholstery, cosmetics, dental floss, and firefighting foam. They have contaminated municipal drinking water supplies across the country, been detected in breast milk, and reached Arctic snow.</p>

      <p>By 2018, PFAS were detectable in the blood of <strong>97% of Americans</strong>.</p>

      <p>Communities near manufacturing plants face the most severe contamination. Ongoing litigation against DuPont and 3M — the two largest historical producers — has produced settlements in the billions, along with internal documents showing both companies had evidence of health risks decades before public disclosure. The story was the subject of the 2019 film <em>Dark Waters</em> and multiple investigative journalism projects, but the regulatory response has been slow. The EPA only began setting enforceable drinking water limits for PFAS in 2024.</p>
    </section>

