    <section id="heat-problem" class="reveal">
      <h2>The Heat Problem Nobody Talks About</h2>

      <p>Even if you accept non-stick cookware into your kitchen, the physics of cooking creates specific risks that manufacturers have not been forthcoming about.</p>

      <p>A 2022 study demonstrated that a single scratch on a non-stick surface can release <strong>millions of microplastic particles</strong> containing PFAS directly into food. Metal utensils, abrasive sponges, stacking pans — all common kitchen practices — create the kind of surface damage that turns a "safe" pan into a contamination source.</p>

      <p>When non-stick pans are heated beyond approximately 500°F (260°C) — a temperature easily reached by leaving an empty pan on a burner for a few minutes — the coating begins to decompose, releasing toxic fumes. The phenomenon is informally known as <strong>"Teflon flu"</strong>: fever, chills, and respiratory symptoms from polymer fume inhalation. The fumes are potent enough that bird owners have documented their pet birds dying from exposure during normal cooking — avian respiratory systems being more sensitive canaries in the coal mine, quite literally.</p>

      <p>Perhaps most concerning: as regulatory pressure forced manufacturers to phase out PFOA specifically, many simply replaced it with other PFAS compounds — structurally similar, potentially equally harmful, but lacking the decades of research documentation that made PFOA a known liability. The replacement chemicals (GenX, for example) are marketed as "PFOA-free" — technically accurate and functionally misleading.</p>
    </section>

    <aside class="pull-quote reveal">
      <p>"A single scratch on a non-stick surface can release millions of microplastic particles containing PFAS directly into food."</p>
