    <section id="alternatives" class="reveal">
      <h2>What to Cook With Instead</h2>

      <p>The good news: cooking without non-stick coatings is neither difficult nor expensive. Humans managed it for several thousand years before 1950. The best alternatives are materials that are chemically inert, durable, and well-understood.</p>

      <h3>Borosilicate Glass (Pyrex)</h3>

      <p>The safest option by a wide margin. Borosilicate glass is heat-resistant to 850°C (1,560°F), completely chemically inert, and leaches precisely nothing into food. It is excellent for slow-cooking, soups, sauces, and anything acidic (tomato-based dishes, wine reductions) that would react with metal surfaces. The only caveat: discard any piece with chips or cracks, as compromised glass can shatter under thermal stress.</p>

      <h3>High-Quality Stainless Steel (18/10 Grade)</h3>

      <p>The "18/10" designation indicates 18% chromium and 10% nickel — the chromium creates a passive oxide layer that resists corrosion and minimizes metal leaching. Reputable manufacturers (All-Clad, Demeyere, Fissler) produce cookware that will outlast you. For new stainless steel, a simple pre-leaching step reduces initial metal transfer:</p>

      <ul>
        <li>Boil 1 cup white vinegar with water for 2–3 hours</li>
        <li>Repeat 2–3 times before first use</li>
        <li>This accelerates formation of the protective chromium oxide layer</li>
      </ul>

      <p>Learning to cook with stainless steel does require a minor technique adjustment — preheat the pan, use adequate fat, and don't move food until it releases naturally — but the results are superior for searing and fond development.</p>

      <h3>Cast Iron</h3>

      <p>Well-seasoned cast iron develops a natural non-stick polymer layer through oil polymerization — actual non-stick performance without synthetic chemistry. It is unmatched for high-heat searing and oven-to-stovetop transitions. Best used occasionally rather than as an everyday workhorse, as it does leach small amounts of iron (which is fine for most people, but worth noting for those with hemochromatosis or iron overload conditions).</p>
    </section>

    <div class="info-card my-12 reveal">
      <h4 class="font-serif text-lg font-semibold mb-3 text-primary-700 dark:text-primary-400">Cookware Comparison</h4>
      <ul class="space-y-2 text-sm">
        <li><strong>Borosilicate glass:</strong> Zero leaching, heat-resistant to 850°C — safest option overall</li>
        <li><strong>Stainless steel (18/10):</strong> Minimal leaching after pre-treatment, extremely durable, excellent heat conductivity</li>
        <li><strong>Cast iron:</strong> Natural non-stick when seasoned, some iron leaching (usually beneficial), best for searing</li>
        <li><strong>Non-stick (PTFE/Teflon):</strong> PFAS exposure risk, microplastic release from scratches, toxic fume risk above 500°F</li>
        <li><strong>"PFOA-free" non-stick:</strong> Often uses replacement PFAS compounds with less research — technically compliant, practically uncertain</li>
      </ul>
    </div>

    <section id="action-steps" class="reveal">
      <h2>Practical Steps</h2>

      <p>Complete PFAS avoidance is impossible in 2026 — the contamination is too widespread. But cookware is one of the few exposure sources entirely within your control. The practical steps are straightforward:</p>

      <ul>
        <li><strong>Audit your cookware.</strong> Any non-stick pan with visible scratches, chips, or coating degradation is actively contaminating your food. Remove it</li>
        <li><strong>Replace with glass, stainless steel, or cast iron.</strong> A single quality stainless steel pan and a glass baking dish cover 90% of home cooking needs</li>
        <li><strong>Never heat an empty non-stick pan.</strong> If you keep any non-stick pieces, this is the single most important rule — empty pans reach decomposition temperatures within minutes</li>
        <li><strong>Use wooden or silicone utensils only</strong> on any coated surface to prevent scratch-related particle release</li>
        <li><strong>Test your water.</strong> PFAS contamination in municipal water supplies is more common than most people realize. Home filtration systems with activated carbon or reverse osmosis reduce PFAS levels significantly</li>
        <li><strong>Store food in glass, not plastic.</strong> Extends the same logic beyond the stovetop</li>
      </ul>

      <p>Once exposure sources are reduced, the body does gradually clear PFAS — slowly, over years, but measurably. The half-life of PFOA in humans is approximately 3.5 years; for PFOS, roughly 5 years. Reducing new intake is the single most effective intervention.</p>
    </section>

